<div id="review_2978550283" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2978550283" />
    <a title="Tobias" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34694041-tobias"><img alt="Tobias" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621875776p2/34694041.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2978550283?book_show_action=true">Oct 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tobias" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tobias" href="/user/show/34694041-tobias">Tobias</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/34694041-tobias?shelf=novels">novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2978550283" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2337419020679322734">Mann considered this to be his magnum opus, and, having reached the end of the final book, it&apos;s not hard to see why. In a sense, almost everything he ever tried to do is contained in these 1500 pages: The history a family, the decline and recalibration of civilisation, the obscurement of mythology, the maturation of the dreamer/artist, you fill in the rest. The novel is an absolute wunderkammer. Sometimes it moves at a breathtaking pace, but most often you are encouraged to just stop and look ar</span>
  <span id="freeText2337419020679322734" style="display:none">Mann considered this to be his magnum opus, and, having reached the end of the final book, it's not hard to see why. In a sense, almost everything he ever tried to do is contained in these 1500 pages: The history a family, the decline and recalibration of civilisation, the obscurement of mythology, the maturation of the dreamer/artist, you fill in the rest. The novel is an absolute wunderkammer. Sometimes it moves at a breathtaking pace, but most often you are encouraged to just stop and look around in amazement. Like this, as Mann wrote somewhere else, it is not too unlike the pyramids themselves.<br /><br />I'd recommend reading Exodus 27-50 before you plunge into this, just for good measure, but read all of the Old Testament if you can stomach it. Even though Jacob and Joseph is at the center, Mann layers myth within myth, Bible narratives and apocrypha on top of each other, to the point where they become almost a single narrative. As Erich Auerbach once wrote, the narratives of the Old Testament are full of mystery, omissions and contains little background, and, keeping this in mind, it is unbelievable what Mann does with these characters and founding myths in terms of fleshing them out. I'm pretty certain that Jacob grieving for Rachel is the most unbearable scene I've ever read.<br /><br />It's hard to imagine that someone will wade through what is essentially 1500 pages of biblical expansive exegesis, if you are not already familiar with Mann, and that's perfectly fine. As it is, I will probably read The Magic Mountain or Doctor Faustus a couple of times each before I even consider returning to this. But such is a marathon, right?</span>
  <a data-text-id="2337419020679322734" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


