<div id="review_3225217447" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3225217447" />
    <a title="Lia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/44005555-lia"><img alt="Lia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578446760p2/44005555.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3225217447?book_show_action=true">Apr 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lia" href="/user/show/44005555-lia">Lia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44005555-lia?shelf=bible-as-literature">bible-as-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44005555-lia?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44005555-lia?shelf=nobel-lit">nobel-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44005555-lia?shelf=myth">myth</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44005555-lia?shelf=german-literature">german-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44005555-lia?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44005555-lia?shelf=20th-century">20th-century</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3225217447" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15126798810170984599">The “game” metaphor at the end is both excellent and baffling. It’s incredible that one can dismiss and forgive so much hate and rancor and revenge just by calling it a game, and it’s possible only from the POV of someone who seems to exist outside time, so that 13 years here, 7 years there, 3 days in a pit, are all irrelevant, nothing, like Athena’s clueless response to Odysseus’ accusation that she had abandoned him.<br/><br/>And maybe that’s how enmity can be set aside at all: not confronted, but dismi</span>
  <span id="freeText15126798810170984599" style="display:none">The “game” metaphor at the end is both excellent and baffling. It’s incredible that one can dismiss and forgive so much hate and rancor and revenge just by calling it a game, and it’s possible only from the POV of someone who seems to exist outside time, so that 13 years here, 7 years there, 3 days in a pit, are all irrelevant, nothing, like Athena’s clueless response to Odysseus’ accusation that she had abandoned him.<br /><br />And maybe that’s how enmity can be set aside at all: not confronted, but dismissed. To have a view that encompasses everything, every time scale, every tribe, every custom, so that even rancorous feuds are mere games, a small obstacle on way to fulfilling something “good.”<br /><br />Overall an enjoyable book, I especially love the crossing of various myths and traditions and rituals in the detailed reimagining, so that Joseph might as well be Gilgamesh, and the terrible, tyrannical patriarch is also a rascal, a trickster. <br /><br />The idea of reducing treachery into mere gambits is wonderful, and curious, but it is not without problems. I do have problems with Mann characterizing or whitewashing some of the more heinous deeds (or at least rumors) as mere exchange in tricks (rape, enslavement), or harmless rough-and-tumble play between brothers. <br /><br />I still can’t believe I finished all 1492 pages of this wonderful book! It’s both too long, and not enough.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15126798810170984599" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


