  </div>
    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2689687263" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2689687263" />
    <a title="Jef Sneider" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/122610-jef-sneider"><img alt="Jef Sneider" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1187905464p2/122610.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2689687263?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jef Sneider" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jef Sneider" href="/user/show/122610-jef-sneider">Jef Sneider</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/122610-jef-sneider?shelf=religion">religion</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/122610-jef-sneider?shelf=spiritual-explorations">spiritual-explorations</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/122610-jef-sneider?shelf=israel-middle-east">israel-middle-east</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/122610-jef-sneider?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/122610-jef-sneider?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/122610-jef-sneider?shelf=action-adventure">action-adventure</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2689687263" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4840874689258461460">Stunning! And, you know the story! You have read the biblical version and heard the commentaries, but you have never heard the story told in this way. Jacob, Rachael. Young Joseph. The land from Syria to Egypt. The sun. The moon. The stars. The planets. The constellations. Leah, her heavy lidded eyes. Her fecundity. But the writing. The reality, emotions and causes. I am in awe of the writer. My mouth hangs open as I read. And, in the end, the end of the first book, I cried. I cried as Jacob cri</span>
  <span id="freeText4840874689258461460" style="display:none">Stunning! And, you know the story! You have read the biblical version and heard the commentaries, but you have never heard the story told in this way. Jacob, Rachael. Young Joseph. The land from Syria to Egypt. The sun. The moon. The stars. The planets. The constellations. Leah, her heavy lidded eyes. Her fecundity. But the writing. The reality, emotions and causes. I am in awe of the writer. My mouth hangs open as I read. And, in the end, the end of the first book, I cried. I cried as Jacob cried over the loss of his beloved Rachael, age 41, who died during childbirth. Poor Dinah. I read her story first, then started “Stories of Jacob,” the first book, and then back to the introduction - Descent into Hell - as suggested by the translator, and the first chapter, At the Well, which is the most beautiful of them all, giving a taste of what a writer is capable of. The first book has ended: three more remain to delight, enlighten and entertain. I shall read on!<br /><br />The second book is “Young Joseph,”and the beautiful and engaging writing style continues. As the story unfolds, the author struggles along with us to fill in the details of a story well known. How can one write with suspense or tension when everyone, writer and reader, knows how it will turn out. “The story tells itself” in real time, he writes even as we read the re-telling and the author writes it. <br /><br />Joseph’s love for his little brother, Benjamin, and their lives together form the most beautiful part of this book. While the dialogue between the two has the vocabulary of a professor of English and the complexity of a Shakespeare verse, the feeling between the two and their bond, as two children with the same mother, makes palpable a real relationship and their love for one another. Benjamin’s unfortunate guilt for the death of his mother in childbirth is heartrending.<br /><br />If you read nothing else, read the chapter called, "The Lesson." Young Joseph's work in the fields and as a shepherd did not fill all his time. He was, after all, the spoiled "child of the one true wife," and he had time for other activities. For one thing, he gets an education in the known science and mathematics of the age from his tutor, Eliezer, for whom "the earth had lept up to greet him" as he sought Rebeccah at the well for Isaac. The story takes place 3000 years ago. What did they know of the planets and mathematics, and what could the aging servant of a man like Jacob teach his precocious son? I was surprised! In beautiful and engaging language the author takes us on a trip through the planets and the calendar, through numbers and their numerical and spiritual meanings, every part of the lesson laced with knowledge of God and history. This is my favorite chapter in the book.<br /><br />Of course, we all know where this story is going as Joseph manages to get Jacob to give him the famous many colored garment; in this case a lavishly embroidered garment worn by Rachael when she was wedded with Jacob, hence the garment of Joseph’s mother, but also the garment bestowing honor and blessing upon the first son of the one true wife. To the other brothers, the ten other than Benjamin and Joseph, this seems to be an obvious blessing bestowed upon Joseph as it comes on the heels of the disgrace of Reuben, first born of Leah, who is punished, losing his blessing as the first born, for the indiscretion of sleeping with Jacob’s concubine and Leah’s servant, Bilhah. <br /><br />This cannot end well, and it does not. It is torture to read about Joseph’s fall, his decent into the pit and his pitiful state as the brothers leave him to die and then ultimately sell him into slavery. Every detail is wrought with care, obviously after much research and creative thought. In the end, the retelling of a story whose ending we already know still leaves us awed and breathless.<br /><br />The third book is “Joseph in Egypt.” I can believe that it took Mann over 20 years to write this collection of four books retelling the biblical story because the detail describing Joseph’s entry into Egypt and the Egyptian gods, their culture and traditions, the details of their economy and their political structures is overwhelming. We know what happens. Joseph is blessed and eventually becomes the chief steward to Potiphar, a favored friend of the Pharoah. <br /><br />In the biblical version there are just a few verses which then describe how Potiphar’s wife tries to seduce Joseph into lying with her. When he refuses, she becomes incensed, rips his tunic from his shoulders as he tries to run away and uses that as evidence that he tried to force her into submission. Once again, a garment is Joseph’s downfall; again his own tunic, and if Jacob believes that Joseph is dead when he sees the bloody many colored garment, Potiphar has to believe that Joseph is guilty when he is shown the visible proof of the matter.<br /><br />A simple story, right? Well, not to Thomas Mann. In these few biblical verses, Thomas Mann sees a challenge. How can one explain the relationship between the wife of a powerful Egyptian vassle of the Pharoah and a lowly Hebrew slave? In his response to this conundrum, the author give an extended answer, entering the mind of the beautiful Mut-en-enet, first wife and most elevated woman in the harem as well as a singer and dancer and priestess of the god Amun. Never was an unrequited love explored in all its mystery and painful development than here, taking up the majority of the book describing Joseph’s life in Egypt before he is thrown into the pit for a second time, again betrayed by a garmnent of clothing, the first of which he should not have worn and the second of which he would have done better top keep on his back!<br /><br />And, we know what is going to happen all along, making the author’s extended exposition frustrating and exasperating. Finally, aware of our pain even as he enjoys continuing to drag this story out in exquisite detail, he writes, “The audience’s [that would be us, the readers] impatience to be told what everyone knows has doubtless reached its peak by now.” And the reader responds, yes! It has! I know how this will end, just give me the details!<br /><br />The final denoumont is done well and Potiphar acts with surprising intelligence and understanding as he assigns Joseph to Pharoah’s prison, “for you will no longer belong to me, but to Pharaoh and are a slave of the king. “ Ahah! And we know where that leads: Book four, “Joseph the Provider.”<br /><br />The final book of the set chronicles Joseph's rise from prison to be the steward of Egypt's agrarian economy, and his eventual reunification with his brothers and his father. Here the author faces another challenge. The bible simply reads that after Joseph's interpretation of his dreams, Pharaoh recognizes Joseph's brilliance, saying, "there is none so discreet and wise as thou" and chooses him to be the overseer of the strategy to save Egypt, and much of the known world, from famine. How could this happen? How could Pharaoh, who is a god himself, surrounded by a court and advisors, make such a choice, impulsively and in the course of a single day? <br /><br />Like the story of Potiphar's wife and her infatuation with the slave from the west, Mann chooses here to expound and and expand the conversation between Joseph and Pharaoh (and Pharaoh's mother the royal consort who had ruled Egypt until her son achieved the necessary age and maturity). Pharaoh is not interested in the management of the empire. As Pharaoh himself responds to Joseph's request for 70 days leave to bury his father in his homeland, he is concerned about the difficulty he will have managing the land in the time of famine without Joseph, saying "My Majesty understands little of all that - my interest has always been in the light above."<br /><br />So, here we digress and expound and expand into a very interesting discussion of that "light above," for Pharaoh himself is not only a god and a man, he is the son of a god, for wasn't Pharaoh's deceased father also Pharaoh and also a god, now in Heaven? So he discusses the meaning of being a god and the son of a god with the spirit of god and references to a threefold godhead, intertwined with Joseph's own twice death and resurrection, once into the pit and once into prison, and the names of both Joseph and Pharaoh which change during their lives. This takes a while, but revolves and the story goes, in favor of Jospeh. These discussions, as with many other passages in the book, presage much of the religious conversations and writings to come thousands of years later. <br /><br />Only after this long conversation is the author finally able to allow the young Pharaoh, over the objections of his mother, of course, "with a boy's exuberant eagerness" and a clap of his hands, to name Joseph as the "Pharaoh's Supreme Mouth, his Grand Vizier, Friend of God's Harvest, Spender of Shade to the King and Father of Pharaoh, Prince of the Interior and Vice-God, and Pharaoh's Unique Friend."<br /><br />From here the story tears ahead, as though Mann's 20 year journey from Germany to Switzerland to Princeton and eventually California was tumbling forward with greater and greater speed drawing the story of Joseph with him, through the 5 years of surplus and plenty, or was it seven? And is there a difference to people when things are going well - who's counting? And into the lean years, the story of Jacob and his sons, the tricks and devices used by Joseph to finally see his brother from the one true wife, Benjamin, the reconciliation and meeting with his father, Jacob, as the entire family, numbering 70 souls (or more), moves from Hebron in the land of Canaan to the fertile pastures of Goshen in the Two Lands of Egypt, of Menassah and Ephraim and most especially to explain Joseph's future place in the history of the people and the story of Abraham, Isaac and Jacob. <br /><br />Foretelling Moses, who will not be allowed to enter into the promised land, Joseph has been "set apart" from his people, and the future of people shall not be through him, but through his brothers and especially the line of Judah. There is no tribe of Joseph, but Jacob adopts Ephraim and Menassah to carry on Joseph's line for him.<br /><br />All of this is told in beautiful language, with grace and dignity, and with a wry sense of awareness that it is a story and that we all know what will happen, and I read the conversations between Joseph and Jacob and his brothers with tears even though I also knew the whole story, how it started and how it ended and who would live and who would die.<br /><br />One last comment: Through all the book, the origin stories of Adam and Eve and Cain and Abel and Noah and his sons and Abraham the Chaldean from Ur, and the almost sacrificed Isaac and the servant, Eliezer for whom the earth had leapt up to greet him, and the trickery between Rebeccah and Isaac and Jacob and Esau and all the stories of Genesis are repeated in one beautiful way after another, over and over. At the end of 1492 pages one can understand how the repetition of such stories over generations would create a real, yet stylized version of the greater story that has become the bible. Thomas Mann tries to bring this story back to "the story as it happened" - filling out the characters and the action so that we can understand how these things could have happened and how these lives were lived, so that now we all know the story, how it started and how it ended, and who lived and who died.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4840874689258461460" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


