<div id="review_3461699032" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3461699032" />
    <a title="Thomas Guidotti" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/71643871-thomas-guidotti"><img alt="Thomas Guidotti" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1556234515p2/71643871.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3461699032?book_show_action=true">Sep 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thomas Guidotti" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thomas Guidotti" href="/user/show/71643871-thomas-guidotti">Thomas Guidotti</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/71643871-thomas-guidotti?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/71643871-thomas-guidotti?shelf=german-austrian">german-austrian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3461699032" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer831152216389077775">This took me a while but that&apos;s not because it was boring in any way whatsoever, rather the book is a really stunning accomplishment in modern literature that demands a thorough and attentive reading. After all it took Thomas Mann 16 years to complete the novel. It is criminal that when people discuss Thomas Mann&apos;s works this book is extremely overlooked because he himself viewed it as his best work and after reading it myself I would say that it is hard to argue otherwise. This book is the lite</span>
  <span id="freeText831152216389077775" style="display:none">This took me a while but that's not because it was boring in any way whatsoever, rather the book is a really stunning accomplishment in modern literature that demands a thorough and attentive reading. After all it took Thomas Mann 16 years to complete the novel. It is criminal that when people discuss Thomas Mann's works this book is extremely overlooked because he himself viewed it as his best work and after reading it myself I would say that it is hard to argue otherwise. This book is the literary equivalent of the music of Wagner in the sense that it is a story of recurring motifs playing themselves out over and over again in the lives of Jacob and Joseph. These characters identify themselves with the myths of their forefathers and they see these stories playing out in their own lives. When Jacob thinks of the story of Abraham leading his people to Egypt during a time of famine (the "descent into the underworld", a recurring motif) he identifies his fleeing from Esau's wrath after cheating him out of his birthright as a recurrence of this same theme in his own life. When Joseph is sold into slavery by his brothers and descends into Egypt he clearly associates this story with Jacob's sojourn in Mesopotamia with Laban. From the beginning of the novel Mann asks the readers to think about whether the stories and myths we are told of the heavens above are a reflection of our own lives on earth or rather is it the other way around. In the preface to the novel Mann discusses the presence of the myth of the flood in every early culture, including the Biblical story of the flood, the story of the flood in the epic of Gilgamesh, and early Chinese tradition. Is this just a story that somehow arose independently in each culture or is it a reflection of some ancient primal flood that has been preserved through thousands of years of oral tradition? <br /><br />Another really key theme to this novel is the contrast between monotheism and polytheism. Every other character outside of the tribe of Israel identifies themselves with their own gods and Jacob and Joseph's conflicting views play a central part of the narrative. Probably my favorite scene in the entire book comes around a third of the way into the fourth book when Joseph and Pharaoh discuss the nature of Aton in contrast to the Hebrew God. Pharaoh (and the Egyptians in general) identifies his gods with signs made manifest to human eyes, whether that means the sun, the moon, the stars, or animals. When Joseph challenges this idea with the belief that even the god that Pharaoh believes is behind these images is but itself a mere shadow of his own God Pharaoh begins to question the nature of his own belief. The idea that even if you were to glimpse the shadow of the things that we see with our own eyes that there is another shadow that lies beyond is the other key to the novel. </span>
  <a data-text-id="831152216389077775" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


