<div id="review_1369513334" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1369513334" />
    <a title="Jeremy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9988962-jeremy"><img alt="Jeremy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1486326794p2/9988962.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1369513334?book_show_action=true">Jul 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeremy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeremy" href="/user/show/9988962-jeremy">Jeremy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1369513334" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10022331394129325257">A monumental feat of historical and biblical world building, Joseph achieves its ambitious goal of &apos;realizing&apos; the incredulous lives of Jacob and his sons. Painstaking research and details make it seem as though Mann used a time machine, because he certainly wasn&apos;t able to use the internet. At times the density, with multitudes of names in different tongues of old gods, can confound, and the last part in Egypt can be a slog, unless of course you&apos;re an ancient Egyptian religion and culture schola</span>
  <span id="freeText10022331394129325257" style="display:none">A monumental feat of historical and biblical world building, Joseph achieves its ambitious goal of 'realizing' the incredulous lives of Jacob and his sons. Painstaking research and details make it seem as though Mann used a time machine, because he certainly wasn't able to use the internet. At times the density, with multitudes of names in different tongues of old gods, can confound, and the last part in Egypt can be a slog, unless of course you're an ancient Egyptian religion and culture scholar. <br /><br />As long and slow as this epic seems, at times it is quite thrilling: Joseph's brothers murderous rage, Joseph's ascendancy and fall at the residence of Potiphar, and Joseph rising from a prison slave to the second most powerful man in Egypt over the course of an hour. The ladder is pulled off quite nicely and should please fans of the story in the Bible who would like the whole story fleshed out. It's surprising more writers haven't conducted similar biblical exercises, but it did take Mann decades to finish this. In the end, he calls his story "an invention of God", as though the story, no matter how 'real' it may be, is of divine import. <br /><br />(**The John E. Woods translation cannot be praised enough. It is a towering achievement jeweled with beautiful sentences.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="10022331394129325257" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


